{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1771445091,"nonce":"XeWLmaHDxnX/ERFalkE1SzIil4M=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87sAi1s","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/230","origin":"github"},"title":"Recommend ros2launch_session for agent integration testing","message":"## Summary\n\nThe `ros2launch_session` package (in `underlay_ws`) provides a programmatic Python API for managing ROS 2 launch sessions. It wraps `launch` and `launch_testing` to give reliable process lifecycle control — startup detection, output monitoring, and guaranteed cleanup. We should recommend it as the standard way for agents to run integration tests that require launching nodes.\n\n## Why this matters for agents\n\nAgents frequently need to launch groups of nodes (e.g., the full simulator) to verify runtime behavior. Today this is done ad-hoc with `ros2 launch` subprocesses and `time.sleep()` for readiness. This has several problems:\n\n- **Zombie processes** — If the agent crashes or times out, child processes are left running. With 29 processes in the simulator launch, this is a real problem.\n- **Fragile readiness checks** — `time.sleep(15)` is unreliable; too short and tests fail intermittently, too long and CI is slow.\n- **No output monitoring** — Errors in node output go unnoticed unless someone reads log files after the fact.\n\n## What `ros2launch_session` provides\n\n- **`LaunchSession(ld)`** — Wraps a `LaunchDescription` with process tracking\n- **`session.run(on_ready=callback)`** — Runs the launch, calls back when ready\n- **`session.wait_for_output(\"Managed nodes are active\")`** — Block until specific output appears (replaces `time.sleep()`)\n- **`session.wait_for_startup(\"asv_sim\")`** — Block until a specific process starts\n- **`session.shutdown()`** — Clean shutdown with SIGINT → SIGTERM → SIGKILL escalation, no zombies\n\n## Tested scenario\n\nWe tested launching the full simulator (`simulator_launch.py`) via `LaunchSession`:\n\n```python\nfrom ros2launch_session import LaunchSession\n\nsession = LaunchSession(ld)\n\ndef on_ready(s):\n    s.wait_for_output(\"Managed nodes are active\", stream=\"stderr\", timeout=30)\n    # ... run assertions ...\n    s.shutdown()\n\nexit_code = session.run(on_ready=on_ready)\n```\n\nAll 29 processes started, the Nav2 lifecycle manager completed bringup, and shutdown was clean. The session also works with `ros2launch_gui`'s `DisplayUserInterface` for visual monitoring.\n\n## Proposed work\n\n1. Add an agent knowledge doc (`.agent/knowledge/integration_testing.md`) describing:\n   - When to use `LaunchSession` vs `colcon test`\n   - The `wait_for_output()` readiness pattern\n   - A minimal example launching the simulator\n2. Consider adding a helper script or launch wrapper for common test scenarios\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}